{"cursor":"2031","size":15,"audio":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/1e/IdiyappamMaking.ogg"],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Idiyappam' (), (), () or 'string hoppers' is a traditional Kerala, Tamil\nand Sri Lankan food consisting of rice flour pressed into noodle form and\nthen steamed.\n\nIdiyappam is culinary specialty in Tamil Nadu, Kerala, and coastal areas of\nKarnataka (especially in the districts of Dakshina Kannada and Udupi). It is\nalso a culinary specialty in Sri Lanka. The name idiyappam derives from the\nTamil words idi meaning ground down and appam the name for dishes of steamed\nrice flour. The dish is also, less frequently, called noolappam or noolputtu\nfrom the Tamil nool meaning string. In coastal areas of Karnataka it is also\ntermed semige.\n\nIt is made of rice flour or wheat flour, salt and water. It is generally served\nas the main course at breakfast or dinner together with a curry (potato, egg,\nfish or meat curry) and coconut chutney. It is also served with sweetened\ncoconut milk in the Malabar region of Kerala. It is not usually served at lunch.\nUsing wheat flour in its preparation gives it a brownish hue.\n","linknr":134,"url":"String_hopper","recorded":1364049728,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Idiyappam&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Idiyappam&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Idiyappam","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia